1.3 Confidence Interval

Boxplots show how the medians of the two distributions compare, but we can also compare the means of the distributions using either a confidence interval or a hypothesis test. Note that when we calculate the mean, SD, etc. weight in these groups using the mean function, we must ignore any missing values by setting the na.rm = TRUE.

# calculating CI stats for students who exercise less than 3 days a week 
Lower_3 <- yrbss %>%
  filter(physical_3plus == "no") %>% 
  summarise(
    mean_weight=mean(weight,na.rm=TRUE),
    sd_weight=sd(weight, na.rm=TRUE),
    count_weight=n(),
    se_weight=sd_weight/sqrt(count_weight),
    t_critical=qt(.975,count_weight-1),
    margin_of_error=t_critical*se_weight,
    weight_low=mean_weight-margin_of_error,
    weight_high=mean_weight+margin_of_error
    )

# calculating CI stats for students who exercise at least 3 days a week
Morethan_3 <- yrbss %>%
  filter(physical_3plus == "yes") %>% 
  summarise(
    mean_weight=mean(weight,na.rm=TRUE),
    sd_weight=sd(weight, na.rm=TRUE),
    count_weight=n(),
    se_weight=sd_weight/sqrt(count_weight),
    t_critical=qt(.975,count_weight-1),
    margin_of_error=t_critical*se_weight,
    weight_low=mean_weight-margin_of_error,
    weight_high=mean_weight+margin_of_error
    )

1.4 Hypothesis test with formula

Write the null and alternative hypotheses for testing whether mean weights are different for those who exercise at least 3 times a week and those who donât.

The null hypothesis for this test is that there is not a significant difference in weight between those who exercise at least 3 times a week and those who exercise less. Our alternative hypothesis is there is a difference in weight for those who exercise at least three times a week and those who donât.

1.5 Hypothesis test with infer

Next, we will introduce a new function, hypothesize, that falls into the infer workflow. You will use this method for conducting hypothesis tests.

But first, we need to initialize the test, which we will save as obs_diff.

library(infer)

obs_diff <- yrbss %>%
  drop_na() %>% 
  specify(weight ~ physical_3plus) %>%
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("yes", "no"))

Notice how you can use the functions specify and calculate again like you did for calculating confidence intervals. Here, though, the statistic you are searching for is the difference in means, with the order being yes - no != 0.

After you have initialized the test, you need to simulate the test on the null distribution, which we will save as null.

null_dist <- yrbss %>%
  drop_na() %>% 
  
  # specify variables
  specify(weight ~ physical_3plus) %>%
  
  # assume independence, i.e, there is no difference
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>%
  
  # generate 1000 reps, of type "permute"
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute") %>%
  
  # calculate statistic of difference, namely "diff in means"
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("yes", "no"))

Here, hypothesize is used to set the null hypothesis as a test for independence, i.e., that there is no difference between the two population means. In one sample cases, the null argument can be set to point to test a hypothesis relative to a point estimate.

Also, note that the type argument within generate is set to permute, which is the argument when generating a null distribution for a hypothesis test.

We can visualize this null distribution with the following code:

ggplot(data = null_dist, aes(x = stat)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  labs (title = "Null distribution",
        x = "",
        y = "Count")

Now that the test is initialized and the null distribution formed, we can visualise to see how many of these null permutations have a difference of at least obs_stat of 1.53?

We can also calculate the p-value for your hypothesis test using the function infer::get_p_value().

null_dist %>% visualize() +
  shade_p_value(obs_stat = obs_diff, direction = "two-sided")

null_dist %>%
  get_p_value(obs_stat = obs_diff, direction = "two_sided")
## # A tibble: 1 Ã 1
##   p_value
##     <dbl>
## 1       0

This the standard workflow for performing hypothesis tests.

library(ggrepel)

director_df <- movies %>% 
  
  #Filtering the required directors - Steven Spielberg and Tim Burton
  filter(director %in% c("Steven Spielberg", "Tim Burton")) %>% 
  
  #Calculate Confidence interval stats for mean ratings for Steven Spielberg and Tim Burton
  group_by(director) %>% 
  summarise(mean_ratings = mean(rating),
            count = n(),
            sd = sd(rating),
            t_critical = qt(0.975, count-1),
            se_ratings = sd / sqrt(count),
            margin_of_error = t_critical * se_ratings,
            lower_ratings = mean_ratings - margin_of_error,
            higher_ratings = mean_ratings + margin_of_error
  )


#Plot replication 
ggplot(director_df, aes(x=mean_ratings, y=fct_reorder(director, mean_ratings),
                        color = director)) +
  
  #Plot mean rating for each director along with value labels
  geom_point(size=3) +
  geom_text_repel(aes(label=round(mean_ratings, 2))) +
  
  #Plot the horizontal CI plot for mean ratings for both directors along with value labels
  geom_errorbar(aes(xmin = lower_ratings, xmax = higher_ratings, 
                    width=.1), 
                size=1.5) +
  geom_text(aes(label=round(lower_ratings, 2), size=2, hjust=4, vjust=-1.5)) +
  geom_text(aes(label=round(higher_ratings, 2), size=2, hjust=-3, vjust=-1.5)) +
  
  #Add rectangle plot to highlight the overlap of mean ratings for the 2 directors
  geom_rect(aes(xmin=
                  min(max(director_df$lower_ratings), 
                      min(director_df$higher_ratings))),
                xmax= 
                  max(max(director_df$lower_ratings), 
                      min(director_df$higher_ratings)),
            ymin=0, ymax=1000,
            colour="white", size=0.5, alpha=0.2) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  
  #Adding labels
  labs(title = "Do Spielberg and Burton have the same mean IMDB ratings?",
       subtitle = "95% confidence intervals overlap",
       x = "Mean IMDB Rating",
       y = "")

3 Omega Group plc- Pay Discrimination

At the last board meeting of Omega Group Plc., the headquarters of a large multinational company, the issue was raised that women were being discriminated in the company, in the sense that the salaries were not the same for male and female executives. A quick analysis of a sample of 50 employees (of which 24 men and 26 women) revealed that the average salary for men was about 8,700 higher than for women. This seemed like a considerable difference, so it was decided that a further analysis of the company salaries was warranted.

You are asked to carry out the analysis. The objective is to find out whether there is indeed a significant difference between the salaries of men and women, and whether the difference is due to discrimination or whether it is based on another, possibly valid, determining factor.

3.2 Relationship Salary - Gender ?

The data frame omega contains the salaries for the sample of 50 executives in the company. Can you conclude that there is a significant difference between the salaries of the male and female executives?

Note that you can perform different types of analyses, and check whether they all lead to the same conclusion

. Confidence intervals . Hypothesis testing . Correlation analysis . Regression

Calculate summary statistics on salary by gender. Also, create and print a dataframe where, for each gender, you show the mean, SD, sample size, the t-critical, the SE, the margin of error, and the low/high endpoints of a 95% condifence interval

# Summary Statistics of salary by gender
Summary_statisics <- mosaic::favstats (salary ~ gender, data=omega)
    
# Dataframe with two rows (male-female) and having as columns gender, mean, SD, sample size, the t-critical value, the standard error, the margin of error, and the low/high endpoints of a 95% confidence interval
Adv_stats <- omega %>% 
  group_by(gender) %>% 
  summarise(
            mean = mean(salary),
            SD = sd(salary),
            count = n(),
            t_critical = qt(0.975, count - 1),
            SE = SD / sqrt(count),
            margin_of_error = t_critical * SE,
            CI_low  = mean - margin_of_error,
            CI_high  = mean + margin_of_error
            )

# Print out Adv_stats

What can you conclude from your analysis? A couple of sentences would be enough

As the two confidence intervals do not overlap, we can say with 95% confidence that there is a significant difference in salaries between women and men. In the given sample, women have a lower mean salary than men. However, since the sample size is not large enough, further analysis would need to be made to make inferences about the population.

You can also run a hypothesis testing, assuming as a null hypothesis that the mean difference in salaries is zero, or that, on average, men and women make the same amount of money. You should tun your hypothesis testing using t.test() and with the simulation method from the infer package.

# hypothesis testing using t.test() 
t.test(salary ~ gender, data=omega)

Obs_stat_omega <- omega %>%

null_dist_omega <- omega %>%
  # specify variables
  specify(salary ~ gender) %>%
  
  # assume independence, i.e, there is no difference
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>%
  
  # generate 1000 reps
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute") %>%
  
  # calculate statistic of difference, namely "diff in means"
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("male", "female"))

ggplot(data = null_dist_omega, aes(x = stat)) +

What can you conclude from your analysis? A couple of sentences would be enough

The absolute t-value is greater than 4,the p value is lower than 5 % and the CI does not include 0, therefore we reject the null hypothesis and we can infer that there is a significant difference in mean salaries of women and men. Looking at the scatterplot, there is a strong correlation between experience and salary. However, there seems to be no clear difference in salary for man and women with similar amount of years of experience (5 - 20 years). We do acknowledge that there are a larger number of women who have little to no experience and are paid less while there is a greater proportion of men with more experience and higher salaries. Therefore, the differences in salaries can mostly be explained by the wide differences in experience, which can also be seen looking at the high correlation coefficient of 0.803 between salary and experience.

5 Challenge 2:GDP components over time and among countries

At the risk of oversimplifying things, the main components of gross domestic product, GDP are personal consumption (C), business investment (I), government spending (G) and net exports (exports - imports). You can read more about GDP and the different approaches in calculating at the Wikipedia GDP page.

The GDP data we will look at is from the United Nationsâ National Accounts Main Aggregates Database, which contains estimates of total GDP and its components for all countries from 1970 to today. We will look at how GDP and its components have changed over time, and compare different countries and how much each component contributes to that countryâs GDP. The file we will work with is GDP and its breakdown at constant 2010 prices in US Dollars and it has already been saved in the Data directory. Have a look at the Excel file to see how it is structured and organised

The first thing you need to do is to tidy the data, as it is in wide format and you must make it into long, tidy format. Please express all figures in billions (divide values by 1e9, or \(10^9\)), and you want to rename the indicators into something shorter.

Secondly, recall that GDP is the sum of Household Expenditure (Consumption C), Gross Capital Formation (business investment I), Government Expenditure (G) and Net Exports (exports - imports). Even though there is an indicator Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in your dataframe, I would like you to calculate it given its components discussed above.

What is the % difference between what you calculated as GDP and the GDP figure included in the dataframe?

library("dplyr")
library("data.table")

# create a tidy dataset for visiualization
given_GDP_data <- UN_GDP_data %>% 
  filter(IndicatorName == "Gross Domestic Product (GDP)") %>% 
  pivot_longer(c(4:ncol(UN_GDP_data)),names_to = "year",values_to="amount") %>% 
  mutate(amount = amount / 1e9)

# calculate simplified GDP and percentage difference                      
GDP_calculation <- tidy_GDP_data %>% 
  filter(IndicatorName %in% old_name) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = IndicatorName, values_from = amount) %>%
  setnames(.,old=old_name,new=new_name) %>% 
  mutate(.,NetExport = Exports - Imports, simplified_GDP = `Gross capital formation` + `Government expenditure` + `Household expenditure` + NetExport) %>% 
  mutate(given_GDP = given_GDP_data$amount) %>% 
  mutate(GDP_percentage_diff = (simplified_GDP / given_GDP)-1)

# Please note: for this exercise we chose to focus on Germany, India and the United States to investigage the % difference in calculated GDP and GDP figure given in the dataframe

# Mapping the % difference in calculated GDP and GDP figure given in the dataframe for Germany, India and the United States 
GDP_calculation %>% 
  filter(Country %in%  c("Germany", "India", "United States")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(year,GDP_percentage_diff, group=Country, colour = Country))+
    geom_line()+
    theme_bw() +
    scale_x_discrete(breaks=seq(1970,2010,10)) +
    scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
    labs (title = "Simplified GDP % difference versus given GDP",
          x = " Year",
          y = "Percentage difference"
          )

Sticking with the countries chosen for the earlier graphs (Germany, India, United States), we can see that the calculated GDP from 1970 to 2010 has always been higher than the GDP given by the United Nations. However, it is notable that since 2010, the calculated GDP has been almost the same as the given GDP. This might be due to the fact that data for the different components of the GDP has become increasingly accurate over the years. For India however, we can observe large volatility in the calculated GDP compared to the given GDP. Compared to Germany and the United States, this might due to higher inaccuracy in reported data or inability to collect precise data.

> What is this last chart telling you? Can you explain in a couple of paragraphs the different dynamic among these three countries?

Viewing the dynamics in the graph, the largest change in GDP components is in India. In India there is a clear decrease in household expeditures and increase in gross capital formation. This would possibly suggest that a general shift away from short term expenditures towards long term asset acquisitions, such as real estate, may have occurred in the last 20 years.

Looking at the US there is a steady increase in household expenditures overtime which would be consistent with inflation as well as the largest proportion of the US population entering into retirement ages. In 2008 we see a steep drop in gross capital formation as well as an increase in government expenditures which is indicative of the 2008 housing financial crisis.

Germanyâs GDP breakdown appears to be the most stable in nature comparative to India and the US. The most notable dynamic is an increase in Net Exports after 2000. One possible reason for this increase may be associated with an increase in popularity for German manufactured automobiles such as Volkswagen and Audi.
